g.text: Step 2: Common Operations That Break Contiguity

div.p: Key Concept: Tensors have logical shape and physical memory layout. A tensor is contiguous if elements are stored sequentially in memory according to the stride pattern.
Recommendation: Use .reshape() for flexibility. Use .view() only when you KNOW the tensor is contiguous (e.g., right after creation or a .contiguous() call).

div.p: After .transpose(), elements are not stored sequentially. .view() cannot reinterpret non-sequential memory as a different shape.

div.p: Memory addresses: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 Elements: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6] Strides: [3, 1] row-major order
Memory addresses: 0, 3, 1, 4, 2, 5 Elements: [1, 4, 2, 5, 3, 6] Strides: [1, 3] NOT sequential!
Memory Copy: Yes, triggers allocation + copy When to use: Only when .view() is required
No-Op if Contiguous: Just like .view() Copy if Needed: Same as .contiguous().view()

ol.li: Use .view() when performance-critical AND you control the tensor's history
